  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Septic shock remains a major public health problem in industrialized countries, with a
      mortality rate as high as 50%, largely related to multiple organ dysfunction. In addition to
      dysregulated inflammatory response, the pathophysiology of organ failures in septic shock
      involves ischemia-reperfusion processes. Remote ischemic conditioning is a therapeutic
      strategy for protecting organs against the detrimental effects of ischemia-reperfusion
      injury.

      The objective of the present study is to determine whether remote ischemic conditioning can
      limit the severity of organ failure in patients with septic shock.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
